span class=title> The Faded Scale</span><hr size=1> &quot;The Faded Scale&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A rolling mist billows forth from the sharp, uninviting crags and lava ducts of the fabled Skyfire Mountains illuminated by the bright hues cast by the dawning sun slowly rising in its' ever present duty to enforce the inevitable flow of time across Norrath.  Through the mists the movement of a shadow never fully in sight but always hinting to its' presence in the corner of the wary traveler's eye comes to a sudden halt.  Now stopped its' features can be roughly discerned, rugged and beaten scales glistening with the moisture collected from running through the moist mist wrapping the whole of this barren, forsaken land in a saintly embrace.  Aye, at times even the ugliest and most lifeless places of Norrath can produce some of the most beautiful sights that any traveler's eyes can come to rest upon, and this was one of those defined moments.  For in that very second, as the sun rose across the absolute greyness, broken cracks, sharpened crags and deadly lava, the illumination of the Skyfire Mountains and all its' normally uninviting features produced instead the grace, beauty and sheer artistry that the elements over time can only be attributed with.  No hand of man, nor god had ever truly shaped it all, yet in its' primal state it rivaled all that which man and god had strived to create in the image of pristine beauty without the hints of the falsehood always present with their efforts.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp It stood there motionless, apparently mesmerized by the dance of the mists and their play with the beams of light going through their midst.  For a moment the mists and shadows seemed to part company with the traveler, taking their dance elsewhere and in that second more of its' features could be made out.  It wore the red robes that can only be worn by the honored circle of Norrath's monks, in hand a battered staff which had obviously seen countless battles held steadily with one of its' ends firmly planted into the ground.  Its' slitted, sharp grey eyes were slowly taking in all of Skyfire, wise and deliberate in their movement, following the features of the terrain as if never before seen.  Although it appeared relaxed, its' posture was that of a coiled spring, ready to bolt into action at a moments notice in potential response to any sudden threat.  It was clear that this traveler was aged and had seen much for it never let its' guard down even in this serene moment.  In times of war, who can?<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Apparently finished getting its' fill of the early morning splendor it finally moved, lifting the butt of its' staff off the ground and turning back in the direction it was travelling in a sweeping, flowing motion with the litheness that could only be evidenced by a great master.  As it keenly observed the path before it, a lone, faded scale came loose off its' head, floating listlessly to the ground causing the traveler to once again delay its course further.  It kneeled down and picked the scale up in its' fingertips carefully as not to damage the delicate, almost transparent evidence of the monks age.  It began speaking to itself under its' breath in a hissing, male tone.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;The beginnings of another molt Balfoosion, like another age in Norrath being given birth to ever so delicate as this scale.&quot;  Turning to look back across the expanse of Skyfire he continued.  &quot;So much gone through in my time, and so much yet to see, there's much in common between you and I oh' broken land of Norrath...&quot;  His eyes turn to the ground with a welling sadness that could obviously only come from the soul of a battle-hardened, grizzled warrior in remembrance of better days and victories.  &quot;I can only pray that our people remain strong and hold together in our fight, for we must be true to protecting our homes and our heritage.&quot;  Looking back in the distance and then up to the bright ball of the risen sun in the sky he went on.  &quot;Like I hope many others feel, I do not wish to be left with the broken scraps of a world consumed by war, our history forgotten as that of all the civilizations we have conquered in the past...&quot;  The sadness gone in an instant, replaced by unparallelled furor and ferocity he turns back to his path and springs forth at blinding speed growling no longer to himself but to all around.  &quot;As long as I live, I will not be conquered, I will not allow myself to be turned into a part of a fabled empire to be told as ancient history around the hearth's of our enemie's taverns and homes...&quot;<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp In a second he was there, and in the next he was gone...  The only proofs of his prescence were the reverberating, fierce roar that echoed off the rare beauty of all the peaks, crags and valleys of the Skyfire Mountains for all to hear that bright dawn -<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;LONG LIVE THE DARK EMPIRE FOR IT SHALL NEVER FALL!!!&quot;<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And a scale...  Faded with age, scarred by battle and the elements, grizzled by its' determination to remain in place through all its' years and beautiful in its' own right as the dew gleamed across its' surface much like all of the land around it...  Both shaped by the wisdom, purity and strength of things beyond the control of gods or men, both an attestment to the existence of the determination and heart of both a world, and a traveller who cannot be broken. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
<br>
- Balf<br>
